<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Nagaland</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Land of Hornbill</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Nagaland — the Land of Hornbill — is one of India's most extraordinary states: a small, mountainous territory in the far northeast where over 16 major Naga tribes have maintained distinct civilizations for thousands of years, each with their own language, weaving patterns, festivals, oral literature and spiritual cosmology. The state is named after the Naga people — one of the most culturally diverse and proudly distinct indigenous communities in Asia. As recently as the early 20th century, Naga warriors practiced headhunting — a tradition connected to a complex system of honor, valor and cosmic power that shaped every aspect of Naga life. The warrior tradition's aesthetic legacy lives on in the extraordinary headdresses of hornbill feathers, bead jewelry, textiles woven with warrior motifs and the morungs (bachelor dormitories) that are the social and cultural heart of Naga village life. The Hornbill Festival — India's greatest tribal cultural festival — brings all 16 Naga tribes together in Kisama Heritage Village every December, creating a week-long explosion of dance, music, craft, sport and cuisine that has become one of Asia's most celebrated cultural events. Nagaland's landscape is all mountain and forest — the Naga Hills rise steeply from the Brahmaputra plains in the west and fall into the Myanmar hills in the east. The Dzükou Valley in southern Nagaland is one of India's most extraordinary high-altitude landscapes — a valley of seasonal flowers at 2,438 meters that turns vivid green in summer and gold in autumn. The World War II battlefields of Kohima — where the Battle of Kohima (1944) was described by the British as "the Stalingrad of the East" and turned the tide of the entire Pacific War — are among the most historically significant and emotionally moving war memorials in Asia. Nagaland's Christianity — nearly 90% of Nagaland's population is Christian, giving it the country's highest proportion — is deeply woven into the social fabric and has created a unique synthesis with indigenous Naga tradition. The state's music scene — from traditional folk to gospel rock — reflects this synthesis with extraordinary vitality.</p>
