const placesData=[
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Hornbill Festival — Kisama",location:"Kisama Heritage Village, Kohima",desc:"India's greatest tribal cultural festival — every December 1-10, all 16 Naga tribes gather at the Kisama Heritage Village to present their dances, music, crafts, food and sports. Named for the hornbill bird revered across Naga cultures, the festival was started in 2000 to preserve and showcase Nagaland's extraordinary tribal diversity. Traditional warrior dances, log drum competitions, stone-pulling races, fire-making contests and the most elaborate tribal costumes in India create a spectacle unlike any other in the country.",fee:["Rs.200 entry"]},
{emoji:"⚔️",name:"Kohima War Cemetery — Battle of Kohima",location:"Kohima",desc:"The most moving WWII memorial in Asia — the Kohima War Cemetery contains the graves of 1,420 Allied soldiers who died in the Battle of Kohima (April-June 1944), described by the British as 'the Stalingrad of the East'. This battle stopped the Japanese advance into India and turned the tide of the entire Pacific War. The memorial inscription is one of the most famous in military history: 'When you go home, tell them of us and say, for your tomorrow we gave our today.'",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🌺",name:"Dzükou Valley",location:"Kohima-Senapati Border",desc:"One of Northeast India's most spectacular landscapes — a high-altitude valley at 2,438 meters on the Nagaland-Manipur border, carpeted with seasonal wildflowers (Dzükou lily, rhododendrons, iris) that bloom June-September. The valley is accessible by a 4-hour trek from Viswema village or Jakhama. In winter, the brown slopes are haunting in their spare beauty. In summer, the valley floor turns into a natural garden of extraordinary color.",fee:["Permit required"]},
{emoji:"🏘️",name:"Longwa Village — Split by India-Myanmar Border",location:"Mon District",desc:"One of the world's most extraordinary border situations — Longwa village in Mon district straddles the India-Myanmar border, with the Angh (king) of the Konyak tribe's longhouse split directly down the middle so that his bedroom is in Myanmar and his dining room in India. The village's tattooed Konyak elders — the last generation of former headhunters, their faces covered in traditional tattoos marking their warrior deeds — are among the most photographed people in Northeast India.",fee:["Inner Line Permit required"]},
{emoji:"🌳",name:"Naga Heritage Village — Morungs",location:"Kisama & Various Village Morungs",desc:"The morung — bachelor dormitory — is the heart of Naga village life. Each morung is elaborately carved with warrior symbols, clan totems and mythological figures, decorated with hornbill heads and mithun skulls. Young men traditionally learned weaving, carving, oral history, warfare and community responsibility in the morung. Visiting a functioning village morung — like those of Khonoma (the 'green village' of Nagaland) — is one of the most authentic cultural experiences available.",fee:["Village contribution"]},
{emoji:"🐆",name:"Intanki Wildlife Sanctuary",location:"Peren District",desc:"Nagaland's premier wildlife sanctuary — a 202 sq km forest in the Naga Hills sheltering tigers, leopards, wild elephants, gibbons, hornbills (multiple species) and over 300 bird species. The sanctuary's dense tropical forest transitions from plains vegetation to mountain forest — a remarkable ecological gradient. The hornbill species found here — particularly the wreathed and rufous-necked hornbill — are the bird that gives Nagaland its festive name.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Japfu Peak & Khonoma Village",location:"Kohima District",desc:"Japfu Peak at 3,048 meters is Nagaland's second-highest peak and offers extraordinary views across the Naga Hills into Manipur on clear days. Below it, Khonoma — the 'green village' of Nagaland — is India's first green village, known for its community conservation of the Amur falcon and its extraordinary biodiversity. The Khonoma nature reserve was established by the villagers themselves after generations of hunting.",fee:["Village fee"]},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Kachari Ruins — Dimapur",location:"Dimapur",desc:"The mysterious 16th-century ruins of the Kachari kingdom — a field of over 100 mushroom-shaped stone monoliths scattered across Dimapur, their original purpose and arrangement unknown. The Kachari dynasty ruled the Brahmaputra valley before being expelled by the Ahom kingdom. Their remaining monuments are strange, beautiful and entirely unexplained — India's most puzzling archaeological site outside the Indus Valley.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.300 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Pfutsero — Highest Town in Northeast India",location:"Phek District",desc:"At 2,133 meters, Pfutsero is the highest town in Northeast India — a cool, misty Chakhesang Naga community surrounded by dense rhododendron and pine forest. The views across the Naga Hills are extraordinary on clear days, and the town's position on the edge of the Dzükou Valley range makes it the ideal base for highland trekking. In March, the rhododendrons bloom across the surrounding hills in waves of crimson and pink.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Rock Music Capital of Northeast India",location:"Kohima & Dimapur",desc:"Nagaland is the rock music capital of Northeast India — a unique fusion of Western rock influences absorbed through missionary contact and indigenous Naga musical traditions has created a music scene of extraordinary vitality. Bands from Nagaland perform at Hornbill Festival and national stages; the state has produced gospel rock, folk metal and indie artists of real talent. Music is both a cultural tradition and a living contemporary identity expression.",fee:["Festival tickets"]}
