const artsData=[
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Naga Tribal Weaving",location:"Statewide — Each Tribe Distinct",desc:"Each of the 16 Naga tribes has its own weaving tradition — distinct patterns, colors and motifs that function as a visual language of identity. The Ao shawl, the Angami mekhela, the Lotha naga naga and the Konyak body cloth are all immediately recognizable to any Naga as markers of tribe and status. Warrior shawls (worn only by those who performed acts of valor) have specific patterns denied to ordinary men. Every Naga weaving is simultaneously art, identity document and cultural archive."},
{emoji:"🔨",name:"Wood Carving & Morung Art",location:"Statewide",desc:"The most dramatic art form of the Naga tradition — the carved wooden facades, posts and panels of the morung (bachelor dormitory) display the village's history, mythology and warrior achievements. Giant carved figures, intertwined serpents, mithan skulls, hornbill motifs and ancestor faces fill every surface. The Konyak wood carvings of Mon district — massive, fierce and accomplished — are among the finest examples of tribal sculpture in India."},
{emoji:"💎",name:"Bead Jewelry & Warrior Ornaments",location:"Statewide",desc:"Naga bead work is among India's most extraordinary jewelry traditions — elaborate necklaces of carnelian, glass, shell, brass and bone beads in specific combinations that mark tribe, clan, gender and status. The necklace worn by a Naga chief is a complete biography of his lineage. The hornbill feather headdress — combining red hornbill casque, yellow cane framework and black feathers — is the most spectacular ceremonial headgear in India."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Log Drum — Naga Percussion",location:"Statewide",desc:"The log drum (yimrong) is the most important musical and communication instrument of the Naga tribes — enormous hollowed tree trunks, 3-10 meters long, suspended in the morung and beaten with wooden mallets to communicate across valleys. Different rhythm patterns announce danger, festival, death, gathering or war. The carving of a new log drum is a major community event requiring ceremony and collective labor. The sound of a Naga log drum carried across a mountain valley is one of the most elemental sounds in India."},
{emoji:"🎨",name:"Tattoo Tradition — Konyak Elders",location:"Mon District",desc:"The Konyak tribe's tattoo tradition — the most elaborate in India — recorded a man's headhunting achievements on his face and body in permanent geometric patterns. A warrior who took a head received facial tattoos; each subsequent head added more. The last generation of tattooed Konyak elders, now in their 80s and 90s, carry on their faces the living record of a warrior tradition that ended in the 1970s. When this generation passes, the living art of the Konyak tattoo ends."},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Pottery & Ceremonial Objects",location:"Chakhesang & Angami Areas",desc:"Nagaland's pottery tradition — handbuilt without wheel, fired in open wood fires — produces functional and ceremonial objects of great dignity. The Angami tribe's distinctive ceramic jars and the Chakhesang's ceremonial vessels are decorated with geometric patterns that echo weaving motifs. Beyond pottery, the Naga craft tradition includes extraordinary carved and painted wooden bowls, bone flutes, bamboo musical instruments and intricately worked brass objects."}
