const traditionsData=[
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Hornbill Festival",location:"Kisama Heritage Village — December 1-10",desc:"India's greatest tribal cultural festival — ten days when all 16 Naga tribes gather in traditional dress to perform their ceremonial dances, music and sports. Named for the great Indian hornbill, sacred across Naga cultures. Warrior dances with spears and dao (sword), competitive log-drum beating, stone-pulling, fire-making without tools, traditional archery, mithun sacrifice rituals and the most spectacular array of indigenous costumes in Asia. The festival has made Nagaland and Kohima known to the world."},
{emoji:"🌾",name:"Sekrenyi — Angami Festival",location:"Kohima, Angami Villages — February",desc:"The Angami Naga's most important festival — a 10-day purification ceremony in February that marks the beginning of the agricultural year. Men fast, ritually cleanse themselves, and the community renews its bonds through prescribed ceremonies. The Sekrenyi songs are among the most beautiful in the Naga tradition. On the final day, traditional Angami dances are performed in full ceremonial dress. The festival is deeply spiritual — connecting the living community to its ancestral obligations."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Aoling — Konyak New Year",location:"Mon District — April",desc:"The Konyak tribe's spring festival — celebrated at the beginning of April when the flowers bloom in the Naga Hills. Young men and women perform traditional dances in full warrior regalia — including the hornbill feather headdress worn only by the tattooed elders. The festival is a celebration of the earth's renewal and the community's continuity. The dances of the Konyak — vigorous, dramatic, rooted in the warrior tradition — are among the most powerful in Northeast India."},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Miu Festival — Ao Tribe",location:"Mokokchung — February/March",desc:"The Ao tribe's major agricultural festival — a celebration of the harvest with traditional dances, feasting and the renewal of community bonds. The Ao are known for their particularly rich cultural tradition and their early adoption of education: Mokokchung has one of the highest literacy rates in Northeast India. The Miu festival is a bridge between the Ao's ancient indigenous tradition and its sophisticated modern identity."},
{emoji:"🎶",name:"Nagaland Christmas",location:"Statewide — December 25",desc:"Nagaland's Christmas celebration is among the most vibrant in India — with nearly 90% of the population Christian, the state celebrates with carol competitions, church services of extraordinary musical quality (Naga choral singing is renowned), community feasting and the continuation of festivals that overlap with the Hornbill Festival. The Naga gospel choral tradition — large mixed choirs with complex harmonies — represents a synthesis of Western choral music and indigenous Naga vocal power."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Tokhu Emong — Lotha Harvest",location:"Wokha District — November",desc:"The Lotha tribe's harvest festival — a celebration of the year's agricultural blessings with feasting, traditional dances and the renewal of community obligations. Each Naga tribe's harvest festival has its own character: the Lotha's Tokhu Emong is known for its elaborate ritual structure and the distinctive dance forms that accompany it. The festival's date is fixed by the traditional lunar calendar — the community's priest determines the exact timing through natural observation."}
