const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Naga King Chili (Raja Mircha)",location:"Statewide — GI Tagged",desc:"The Bhut Jolokia (ghost pepper / king chili) — one of the world's hottest chilies, producing 1,041,427 Scoville Heat Units — is indigenous to Nagaland and was certified as the world's hottest chili in 2007 by Guinness World Records. In Naga cooking it is used fresh, dried and smoked in almost every preparation. The heat is not a condiment — it is the foundation. Naga food is among the hottest in the world by design and by culture."},
{emoji:"🐷",name:"Smoked Pork with Bamboo Shoot",location:"Statewide",desc:"The quintessential Naga dish — pork smoked over wood fires for hours until deeply flavored, then slow-cooked with fresh or fermented bamboo shoot, Naga king chili and local herbs. The smoke penetrates every fiber of the meat; the bamboo shoot's acid cuts through the fat; the king chili sets everything ablaze. Each Naga tribe has its own version — the Ao, Angami, Konyak and Lotha variants are each distinct in spicing and technique."},
{emoji:"🍚",name:"Galho — Naga Rice Porridge",location:"Statewide",desc:"The everyday comfort food of Nagaland — a thick porridge of rice cooked with pork, smoked fish or vegetables until the rice breaks down into a unified whole. Galho is simultaneously breakfast, post-illness recovery food and festival food. Each family's galho is slightly different — the ratio of rice to water, the specific smoked meat, the local herbs added — making it a dish of infinite variation within a clear tradition."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Akhuni — Fermented Soybean Paste",location:"Angami & Other Tribes",desc:"The most distinctive and controversial ingredient in Naga cooking — soybeans fermented until they develop an intensely pungent, deeply umami paste (akhuni). The smell is powerful; the flavor is transformative. Akhuni is used in chutneys, cooked with pork, stirred into vegetables and eaten as a condiment with rice. It divides visitors sharply — the uninitiated find it overwhelming, the converted find it irreplaceable. It is the truffle oil of Naga cuisine."},
{emoji:"🐟",name:"Dried and Smoked Fish",location:"Statewide",desc:"Nagaland's landlocked position means fish arrive dried or smoked — but this has created a distinct culinary tradition. Dried fish are ground into powders and pastes, cooked with vegetables, used as a flavoring base. The specific dried fish varieties available in Kohima's market — hilsa, catfish, river fish from Assam — each bring different flavor profiles to Naga cooking. Fish and pork together in the same preparation is a combination unique to this region."},
{emoji:"🫘",name:"Anishi — Taro Leaf Preparation",location:"Ao Naga Areas",desc:"A unique Ao Naga ingredient — colocasia (taro) leaves sun-dried, fermented and compressed into dense cakes that are stored for months. Anishi is used like akhuni — as a deeply flavored cooking base. The preparation process is labor-intensive and the result is extraordinarily concentrated. Combined with pork and king chili, it creates a curry unlike any other in Indian cooking — earthy, fermented, ancient and complete."},
{emoji:"🥢",name:"Rice Beer & Zutho",location:"Statewide",desc:"Zutho — the Angami rice beer — is brewed in bamboo or ceramic vessels using cooked rice and a local yeast starter. Clear, mildly alcoholic and pleasantly sour, it is offered to every guest and drunk at every festival and social gathering. The Naga rice beer cultures — each tribe with its own brewing tradition and name — represent a complex fermentation heritage that connects food, hospitality, ceremony and community in a single bowl."},
{emoji:"🌱",name:"Wild Vegetables & Forest Greens",location:"Statewide",desc:"Nagaland's forest landscape provides an extraordinary pantry — fiddlehead ferns, wild mushrooms, banana flowers, bamboo shoots in multiple preparations, wild garlic, edible orchids and dozens of local greens that have no names outside the Naga language. The foraging knowledge of Naga women is encyclopedic — the forest is not wilderness but a cultivated larder. These forest preparations are the most distinctly Nagaland food available, found only in village homes and local markets."}
